WEBVTT

00:00.258 --> 00:07.688
Now, I've got to confess that I'm a very late season Mariners fan.

00:08.369 --> 00:16.900
Having lived most of my life in Washington and having had my heart broken numerous times, I wait till late in the season before I really get on board.

00:16.940 --> 00:21.646
And so, let's see, I guess it was Friday night.

00:22.808 --> 00:25.512
And the eighth inning, I decided it was time to get on board.

00:25.632 --> 00:27.314
I finally turned on the game.

00:30.722 --> 00:33.686
And I figured, you know, one or two innings, how bad could it be?

00:33.726 --> 00:38.994
Turns out I got almost a full baseball game, and after that, it went 15 innings, right?

00:39.174 --> 00:41.177
And we finally won, amazingly.

00:41.818 --> 00:45.323
But I have to admit, I was kind of running out of gas by the time we got to the end.

00:45.343 --> 00:47.987
I mean, it was getting late, you know, and we finally got that run.

00:48.047 --> 00:51.812
And I was thinking about that, just, you know, running out of gas.

00:52.113 --> 00:58.482
And when I was a student in college years ago, I went to a little college up in Alberta, Canada,

00:59.138 --> 01:00.781
And of course, these wide open prairies.

01:01.221 --> 01:02.003
Been out with a friend.

01:02.063 --> 01:03.705
We'd gone driving someplace.

01:03.906 --> 01:12.700
And as college students are want to do, you kind of use all the gas in the tank in some kind of mistaken idea that this is saving money if you don't fill up early.

01:12.740 --> 01:13.942
I don't know what that thought is.

01:14.062 --> 01:18.649
But I was pushing the boundaries of what my gas tank could handle.

01:19.290 --> 01:24.418
And sure enough, a few miles shy of town, we ran out of gas.

01:25.460 --> 01:26.642
And it was late in the day.

01:27.234 --> 01:29.636
And here's the thing about life on the prairies.

01:29.696 --> 01:32.599
You can see a long ways.

01:32.619 --> 01:34.401
And so we're walking toward town.

01:34.461 --> 01:38.185
No, we have a long walk ahead of us looking as it's getting dark, looking at the lights of town.

01:38.245 --> 01:41.848
And we could see the three gas stations in town.

01:42.949 --> 01:45.131
And we got to watch them close.

01:47.373 --> 01:51.698
That is a sad feeling to watch, oh, there goes the lights on that one.

01:51.758 --> 01:52.578
There goes the other one.

01:52.999 --> 01:54.140
Yep, we're really stuck now.

01:54.160 --> 01:56.242
They're all closed.

01:56.674 --> 01:58.576
That's a sad thing when you run out of gas.

01:59.417 --> 02:03.381
Now, we've been going through this series the last few weeks called Long Journey Home.

02:03.882 --> 02:19.239
And we are looking at the journey of the children of Israel from their life of slavery in Egypt, God's deliverance of them from that slavery, and now they're on that journey making their way to a new promised homeland that God has said He's going to give to them.

02:20.040 --> 02:25.906
And we've been looking not just at the stories for their historical value, but also seeing them

02:26.018 --> 02:28.141
some parallels to the Christian life.

02:28.902 --> 02:35.191
And we're not just making that up because throughout the New Testament, you see those parallels, those connections made as well.

02:35.932 --> 02:43.322
And today, we're coming to a story that is kind of about running out of gas, although they didn't need gas, right?

02:43.382 --> 02:44.063
No cars.

02:44.163 --> 02:47.488
I'm sure they would have welcomed a couple buses to help with the journey.

02:47.528 --> 02:48.389
They didn't have that.

02:48.950 --> 02:54.578
But what they did need for going across a wilderness, a desert area, was they need water.

02:55.042 --> 02:58.730
And when you run out of water, you are in as big a trouble.

02:58.790 --> 03:04.181
You're actually in bigger trouble than running out of gas out there on the prairies late at night.

03:05.223 --> 03:16.146
And so today, we're going to take a look at what happened to these very thirsty people when they needed water, but there was none to be had.

03:16.674 --> 03:19.678
And I'm going to warn you in advance, we have a lot of ground to cover, okay?

03:20.519 --> 03:25.145
I think we're going to get through it quicker than the Mariners, completed a baseball game, but we'll see.

03:25.165 --> 03:29.331
Let's take a look at Exodus, chapter 17, the first seven verses.

03:32.255 --> 03:33.997
If my slides will advance.

03:36.700 --> 03:38.142
Are they advancing back there, guys?

03:40.626 --> 03:41.146
There we go.

03:41.627 --> 03:44.050
We'll see if there are more work you might have to help me out this morning.

03:44.450 --> 03:52.840
All the congregation of the people of Israel moved on from the wilderness of sin by stages, according to the commandment of the Lord and camped at Rifadim.

03:53.421 --> 03:55.804
But there was no water for the people to drink.

03:56.765 --> 03:58.207
I think you're going to have to help me out this morning.

03:58.247 --> 03:59.408
Oh, wait, it just woke up.

04:00.710 --> 04:04.935
Therefore, the people quarreled with Moses and said, give us water to drink.

04:05.776 --> 04:08.640
And Moses said to them, why you quarreled with me?

04:08.680 --> 04:10.642
Why do you test the Lord?

04:11.650 --> 04:21.321
But the people thirsted there for water and the people grumbled against Moses and said, why did you bring us up out of Egypt to kill us and our children and our livestock with thirst?

04:22.883 --> 04:26.327
So Moses cried to the Lord, what shall I do with this people?

04:26.427 --> 04:28.089
They are almost ready to stone me.

04:29.671 --> 04:39.282
And the Lord said to Moses, pass on before the people taking with you some of the elders of Israel and taking your hand to staff with which you struck the Nile and go.

04:40.002 --> 04:49.871
Behold, I will stand before you there on the rock and horrib, and you shall strike the rock, and waters shall come out of it, and the people will drink."

04:49.891 --> 04:59.120
And Moses did so in the side of the elders of Israel, and he called the name of the place, Massa and Marabah, because of the quarreling of the people of Israel.

04:59.760 --> 05:04.345
And because they tested the Lord by saying, is the Lord among us or not.

05:05.766 --> 05:09.970
Now it's interesting to take a look at the name that Moses gave to this place.

05:10.178 --> 05:18.431
Masah and Maraba, too bad that most of our English translations simply transliterate the Hebrew.

05:19.232 --> 05:22.958
Because for us as English speakers, that just looks like gibberish.

05:22.978 --> 05:24.460
It doesn't really say anything.

05:24.981 --> 05:27.545
And yet to the Hebrews, these were not nonsense words.

05:27.585 --> 05:28.967
They had real meaning to them.

05:29.929 --> 05:35.457
Oftentimes, when people name places, they come up with things that are maybe descriptive of a unique feature.

05:36.499 --> 05:38.642
Maybe you've been to Twin Falls, Idaho.

05:38.978 --> 05:40.439
You know why it's named that, right?

05:40.459 --> 05:42.041
There's two waterfalls.

05:42.621 --> 05:48.147
Or the little college I went to up in Canada was in a town called Three Hills.

05:48.887 --> 05:54.973
Now, in Alberta, on the prairies, the hills are something you wouldn't need a grading permit to fix around here.

05:55.554 --> 05:57.996
But there, it was a notable enough geographic formation.

05:58.016 --> 06:01.800
They named the town after Three Hills, or squam.

06:02.200 --> 06:05.563
Now, I've heard that squam is an Indian phrase meaning quiet waters.

06:06.064 --> 06:08.306
I've heard people say that it means onions.

06:08.450 --> 06:13.535
I found an article where a tribal linguist says it literally means a place for going to shoot.

06:14.216 --> 06:21.363
So whoever named squim squim back in the day named it something they understood that it said something about the place to them.

06:22.364 --> 06:24.786
Of course, that's the other way that places get named.

06:24.826 --> 06:27.309
It's an experience that someone had there.

06:28.330 --> 06:30.752
Did you know that there's an accident Maryland?

06:31.753 --> 06:36.818
It's called accident because a land speculator accidentally marked the town's boundaries.

06:37.410 --> 06:39.532
Or how about Bug Tussle, Kentucky?

06:41.114 --> 06:44.417
Apparently Bug Tussle had this big problem with wood lights in the hay.

06:44.778 --> 06:50.804
And the workers who had bed down the hay said you had to tussle with the bugs to get a spot to go to sleep.

06:51.965 --> 06:53.527
Or Carefree, Arizona.

06:54.748 --> 07:00.494
That was named by some land developers and they thought that maybe that would attract people to come there for a relaxed lifestyle.

07:01.675 --> 07:04.338
So if you're going to name a spot like this,

07:04.610 --> 07:10.840
where this incredible miracle has happened, where water has come out of a rock, what would you name it?

07:12.002 --> 07:20.655
Well, I'd be tempted to name it something like miracle springs, or maybe wet rock, or gusher valley.

07:20.836 --> 07:22.258
Those all seem like good ideas.

07:23.159 --> 07:27.446
You want to know what Moses chose to name this place in honor of what happened there?

07:29.830 --> 07:30.731
Test and argue.

07:31.432 --> 07:32.594
I just jumped ahead on me there.

07:33.506 --> 07:36.509
Test and argue is the name that he decided to give this place.

07:37.771 --> 07:39.092
That's what stood out to him.

07:40.373 --> 07:46.700
What put this place on the map for Moses was not the incredible miracle of water coming out of a rock.

07:46.780 --> 07:52.327
What put it on the map for Moses was this response the people had when they couldn't find water.

07:52.967 --> 07:55.750
They began to quarrel and argue and test God.

07:56.972 --> 07:59.775
It says that they quarreled with Moses.

08:00.756 --> 08:02.898
They demanded, you got to give us water.

08:03.202 --> 08:07.126
Verse three, it says that they grumbled against Moses.

08:07.186 --> 08:13.152
And that idea of grumble, the Hebrew there has the sense of being permanently stuck in a bad frame of mind.

08:14.113 --> 08:17.496
These people just cannot get out of their frame of mind.

08:17.516 --> 08:19.438
They are stewing in their anger.

08:19.478 --> 08:26.825
And apparently they're getting pretty hot about it because verse four, Moses says to the Lord, they're almost ready to stone me.

08:27.806 --> 08:30.348
I've got a major revolt on my hands.

08:30.388 --> 08:32.210
These people are so upset.

08:32.834 --> 08:37.580
And they even doubted, they even challenged God's presence, verse seven.

08:38.861 --> 08:41.044
Is the Lord among us or not?

08:42.406 --> 08:51.277
After all they've been through, after all they've experienced, when they run into this challenge, their question is, is God even with us?

08:51.377 --> 08:52.258
Does He care?

08:52.318 --> 09:02.290
And I think the reason that those bad attitudes stood out in Moses' mind more than God's miracle is because Moses had come to a place of

09:02.434 --> 09:05.319
genuine faith in God's goodness.

09:06.941 --> 09:11.148
He had no more idea than those people did as to where they were going to get water.

09:12.390 --> 09:13.993
But he had followed where God had led.

09:14.393 --> 09:20.744
He had watched as time and again God had met their need in the most surprising ways.

09:22.587 --> 09:29.458
What really stood out was that these people, after all God had led them through, were still stuck in a rut of unbelief.

09:30.338 --> 09:34.864
Every time they hit what seemed like a dead end, God had provided for them.

09:36.446 --> 09:38.409
They were still collecting manna every morning.

09:38.449 --> 09:40.251
They were still getting quail every night.

09:40.892 --> 09:46.219
They were following this fiery cloud that gave evidence to God's presence going before them.

09:47.180 --> 09:57.394
And yet with thirst setting in, their response is anger, accusation, grumbling, arguing and doubt.

09:58.722 --> 10:07.713
When we get to the New Testament, we discover that the descendants of those ancient people still easily got themselves stuck in doubt whenever problems arose.

10:08.854 --> 10:14.662
Maybe remember the disciples, they get caught in a storm at sea and they run to Jesus.

10:14.702 --> 10:16.464
They woke him up shouting, Lord, save us.

10:16.704 --> 10:18.026
We're going to drown.

10:19.167 --> 10:22.291
In Jesus response, why are you afraid?

10:23.372 --> 10:24.754
You have so little faith.

10:25.506 --> 10:29.990
Then he got up and rebuked the wind and waves, and suddenly there was great calm.

10:31.311 --> 10:33.934
Or, again on the water, you have that story about Peter, right?

10:33.974 --> 10:37.217
When Peter tries walking on water at Jesus' invitation.

10:38.038 --> 10:40.680
But then we're told that Peter saw the strong winds and the waves.

10:40.720 --> 10:41.721
He was terrified.

10:41.761 --> 10:42.642
He began to sink.

10:43.463 --> 10:44.824
Save me, Lord," he shouted.

10:45.885 --> 10:46.746
I'm going to die.

10:48.308 --> 10:49.409
Was Jesus' response?

10:50.970 --> 10:55.154
He reached out, grabbed him, and said, you have so little faith.

10:55.842 --> 10:57.584
Why did you doubt me?

10:58.685 --> 11:00.608
Peter, I'm the one who invited you out of the boat.

11:01.389 --> 11:03.652
Do you think I invited you out of the boat just to let you drown?

11:03.692 --> 11:05.534
Where is your faith?

11:07.456 --> 11:11.261
Later we find the disciples in a conversation with Jesus talking about bread.

11:11.301 --> 11:23.977
We talked about this a bit last week and Jesus uses bread as a metaphor and yet the disciples mistake his words for literal bread and they didn't have any actual bread with them.

11:24.017 --> 11:25.138
So here's what happened.

11:25.730 --> 11:29.495
At this, they began to argue with each other because they hadn't brought any bread.

11:30.317 --> 11:37.247
Jesus knew what they were saying, so he said, you have so little faith, why are you arguing with each other about having no bread?

11:38.208 --> 11:39.550
Don't you understand even yet?

11:39.690 --> 11:50.385
Don't you remember the 5,000 I fed with five loaves, the baskets of leftovers you picked up, or the 4,000 I fed with seven loaves and the large baskets of leftover you picked up?

11:51.687 --> 11:53.650
You've had experience with me.

11:54.594 --> 11:57.557
Why would you be arguing about bread now?

11:59.920 --> 12:04.325
I wish I could say with confidence that we have progressed farther than they.

12:04.365 --> 12:07.789
I'm not so sure we have.

12:09.711 --> 12:13.796
I don't know about you, but I can think of times in my life where I've run into adversity.

12:13.836 --> 12:21.284
And despite the ways that I've seen God lead and provide, my first response has not been a response of faith.

12:21.404 --> 12:23.186
It hasn't been a response of trust.

12:23.586 --> 12:32.237
It has been that response of grumbling, of arguing, of doubting, of thrashing around trying to fix the problem on my own.

12:35.321 --> 12:39.086
But I don't want to spend our time this morning so much on the doubters and grumblers.

12:40.348 --> 12:42.951
I want to spend time thinking about the rock.

12:44.173 --> 12:50.962
And that's because the Apostle Paul saw a very interesting picture hidden in that rock.

12:51.554 --> 12:55.038
This comes out of 1 Corinthians, chapter 10, the first four verses.

12:56.920 --> 13:02.727
Paul says, I do not want you to be unaware brothers that our fathers were all under the cloud, right?

13:02.747 --> 13:19.826
He's talking about the children of Israel now being led by that fiery cloud, all passed through the sea, the dividing of the red sea, all were baptized into Moses, in the cloud and in the sea, and all ate the same spiritual food and all drank the same spiritual drink for

13:19.970 --> 13:26.617
they drank from the spiritual rock that followed them and the rock was Christ.

13:28.158 --> 13:40.371
Now in this passage, Paul goes full throttle in seeing the connections between Israel's physical journey following Moses through the wilderness and the spiritual journey we're on as followers of Jesus.

13:41.272 --> 13:47.378
And the reason he brings us up, his intent was to spur the believers at Corinth to

13:47.490 --> 13:51.356
act on what they said they believed, to live it out.

13:52.718 --> 13:59.009
You wanted them to know that their faith shouldn't simply be a doctrinal statement, but it should be an engagement of the whole person.

14:00.371 --> 14:02.094
Let me give you a little bit of context to this.

14:02.134 --> 14:08.204
You need to back up just prior to this to chapter 9, okay, a section just before that, verses 25 through 27.

14:10.267 --> 14:14.674
He says, every athlete exercises self-control in all things.

14:15.554 --> 14:19.598
They do it to receive a perishable wreath, but we an imperishable.

14:20.759 --> 14:22.361
So I do not run aimlessly.

14:23.482 --> 14:32.812
I do not box as one beating the air, but I discipline my body and keep it under control, lest, after preaching to others, I myself should be disqualified.

14:34.053 --> 14:36.276
Paul says, I have a goal in mind.

14:37.517 --> 14:38.958
It's not just an earthly goal.

14:39.058 --> 14:42.482
It's not just getting a job promotion or a bigger house.

14:42.754 --> 14:47.440
He says, I'm looking forward to a heavenly reward to hear Jesus say, well done.

14:48.281 --> 14:50.504
You have run the race well.

14:50.564 --> 14:54.890
He says, because of that, I don't just flail about.

14:54.910 --> 14:56.993
I'm more like a disciplined athlete.

14:57.013 --> 15:00.597
The things that I do are aiming toward that goal.

15:02.880 --> 15:06.465
He also recognizes that he's living in a wilderness kind of world.

15:06.545 --> 15:10.450
There are all sorts of temptations and distractions.

15:10.658 --> 15:13.341
lesser goals that could take him off course.

15:15.404 --> 15:16.726
His faith demands action.

15:18.528 --> 15:20.130
He says choices have to be made.

15:21.832 --> 15:23.634
Sacrifices are called for.

15:24.295 --> 15:25.857
Discipline is required.

15:27.640 --> 15:38.994
The specific issue that led Paul to this whole discussion has been a debate within the Corinthian church over eating food that had been ritualistically offered to idols.

15:40.034 --> 15:48.664
And actually it appears from some earlier writing here in Corinthians that some of this controversial dining was happening inside of pagan temples.

15:48.784 --> 16:04.281
So it wasn't just that people were picking up things at the supermarket and the shopkeeper mentions off-handedly that the food had been ceremonially offered to his shop's gods or to his favorite Greco-Roman deity.

16:04.942 --> 16:08.946
Rather, these were Christians being invited to religious feasts

16:09.122 --> 16:10.564
inside pagan temples.

16:12.086 --> 16:21.098
And perhaps there were some of them that could do that with a clear conscience because they knew that there was no reality to the supposed gods being honored.

16:22.340 --> 16:28.408
But Paul says there are others for whom the worship of those idols have been a lifestyle of religious bondage.

16:29.910 --> 16:33.074
Spiritually going back to those places is going back to Egypt.

16:33.570 --> 16:35.774
It is going back to the things that enslaved them.

16:35.834 --> 16:41.363
And to see fellow Christians entering into those practices was a huge stumbling block.

16:42.485 --> 16:46.833
It was this siren call back to spiritually dangerous places.

16:48.976 --> 16:54.706
And so with those realities in mind, Paul points his readers back to Israel's journey in the wilderness.

16:56.770 --> 17:14.594
Just as the Corinthian believers had all been baptized into Christ, this public profession of faith, this launching of their journey with Christ, he says, so too had those ancient Israelites experienced a type of baptism, not a Jesus baptism, but a Moses baptism in crossing the Red Sea.

17:16.196 --> 17:20.782
But there were fusals to trust God, to walk in faith.

17:22.024 --> 17:23.286
That's what had been their undoing.

17:24.647 --> 17:26.610
And we've seen this habit, we've seen them

17:26.722 --> 17:36.353
often looking back longingly to the delicacies of Egypt, looking back to an old way of life when things get difficult and even threatening to go back.

17:37.374 --> 17:40.057
We should just get a new leader and we should go back to Egypt.

17:40.077 --> 17:42.600
It was better there to live as slaves.

17:45.163 --> 17:55.154
And one particularly ominous event when the people weren't sure what was up with Moses, we're gonna come to this story shortly, but we find that they actually constructed a replica

17:55.298 --> 18:03.427
of one of the Egyptian gods, a golden calf idol, and they didn't just replicate the idol, they replicated the boisterous parting that went along with it.

18:04.408 --> 18:10.374
They had a drunken riot complete with dancing and sacrifices to the calf idol.

18:11.615 --> 18:16.180
And Paul alludes to that here in 1 Corinthians, chapter 10, verse 7.

18:17.041 --> 18:20.025
He says, do not be idolaters, as some of them were.

18:20.785 --> 18:25.170
As it is written, and now he quotes directly out of Exodus 32, 6,

18:25.506 --> 18:29.710
The people sat down to eat and drink and rose up to play.

18:30.251 --> 18:39.099
That is referring to them entering into these religious orgies that they had seen in Egypt that now they are participating in.

18:39.519 --> 18:40.781
And you can see the connections.

18:41.461 --> 18:49.429
Paul is saying to these Corinthian believers who are being tempted to go back and join into some of the idolatrous practices they have come out of.

18:49.949 --> 18:51.991
He says, don't be like them.

18:52.992 --> 18:54.674
That was their undoing.

18:55.106 --> 18:59.475
be the athlete who is disciplined and focused on the goal.

19:01.018 --> 19:09.274
The end result of returning to such false worship for Israel was that the people fell under God's judgment.

19:09.294 --> 19:13.522
He says, going back to those old ways, you're going to make a shipwreck of your faith.

19:15.010 --> 19:26.107
In worshiping the calf, they made a mockery of the one who had truly delivered them, and Paul uses those dark images to warn the Corinthians away from falling back into their own forms of idolatry.

19:28.230 --> 19:41.650
Now, apologies for taking the detour, but I want you to understand the context that Paul was speaking into as he makes these connections between Israel's wilderness trek and the controversial lifestyles of some believers and Corinth.

19:42.466 --> 19:46.151
It's in that context that he talks about God's provision for his people.

19:46.331 --> 19:51.077
And specifically he talks about this miracle of water from a rock.

19:51.378 --> 19:53.180
That's how this all begins to tie together.

19:54.702 --> 19:59.328
And did you notice he talked about the spiritual rock that followed them?

20:00.871 --> 20:01.972
What was that all about?

20:03.434 --> 20:07.059
Well, there are actually two episodes involving water from a rock.

20:07.599 --> 20:08.581
You probably know this.

20:08.701 --> 20:09.522
The first,

20:09.698 --> 20:11.160
happened early in their travels.

20:11.180 --> 20:13.002
That's the one we just read about this morning.

20:13.702 --> 20:20.730
And in that instance, God told Moses that he should strike the rock and water would come.

20:22.312 --> 20:24.855
The second comes near the end of the wilderness journey.

20:26.337 --> 20:27.818
And once again, they have no water.

20:27.858 --> 20:28.779
The people are upset.

20:28.819 --> 20:29.740
The people are grumbling.

20:29.801 --> 20:32.283
We find that this is a recurring theme in their lives.

20:32.864 --> 20:36.788
And once again, Moses is told that water is going to come from a rock.

20:36.808 --> 20:38.290
But the way he's going to get it

20:38.402 --> 20:39.924
is gonna be different this time.

20:39.964 --> 20:46.491
The first time God said strike the rock, the second time Moses has told simply to speak to the rock.

20:48.192 --> 20:50.495
But we find out in that story that Moses was human.

20:51.396 --> 20:57.342
And after all they've been through with these people, and here they are grumbling once again, Moses is just livid.

20:57.562 --> 21:05.010
He has had it with these people, with their constant doubting, their grumbling, their rebellion, and in his anger,

21:05.090 --> 21:11.419
Rather than doing what he was told to do, which was to speak to the rock, he strikes the rock.

21:12.140 --> 21:13.663
In fact, he hits it twice.

21:14.924 --> 21:16.206
And water does come.

21:17.008 --> 21:26.261
God provides for his people, but Moses is told by God that because of his disobedience, he would not be permitted to enter into the promised land.

21:27.924 --> 21:32.050
Which seems like a pretty heavy penalty for one flash of anger.

21:32.831 --> 21:34.994
But we're gonna talk more about that in just a bit.

21:36.674 --> 21:42.742
Maybe you've heard about the famous sailing stones of racetrack Playa in Death Valley.

21:43.964 --> 21:50.993
For a lot of years, people have been mystified by these rocks that seemingly, magically, move by themselves.

21:51.013 --> 21:55.319
You can see the tracks they leave where they're going, but no one ever saw the rocks move.

21:56.080 --> 21:58.063
And nobody knew really what was going on.

21:58.123 --> 22:06.354
And they didn't actually figure it out until 2014 when scientists actually put GPS trackers on the rocks

22:06.850 --> 22:09.894
and use time-lapse photography to figure out what was going on.

22:10.415 --> 22:12.017
That's a picture of Richard Norris.

22:12.698 --> 22:18.747
He's from the Scripps Institute of Oceanography, why the Institute of Oceanography is in Death Valley, we'll never know.

22:19.829 --> 22:23.314
But he's one of the researchers who made the discovery.

22:24.355 --> 22:31.465
And on the Scripps website, he explains what's going on with these rocks and their mysterious movements.

22:32.767 --> 22:34.770
He says, first, the ply of filled with water,

22:35.362 --> 22:41.290
which has to be deep enough to form floating ice during cold winter nights, but shallow enough to expose the rocks.

22:42.211 --> 22:51.244
As nighttime temperatures plummet, the pond freezes to form thin sheets of window pane ice, which must be thin enough to move freely, but thick enough to maintain strength.

22:52.385 --> 23:04.882
On sunny days, the ice begins to melt and break up into large floating panels, which light winds drive across the playa, pushing rocks in front of them, and leaving trails in the soft mud below the surface.

23:06.210 --> 23:07.391
How crazy is that?

23:09.214 --> 23:18.325
But it turns out that the Scripps Institute researchers weren't the first to hypothesize about floating stones.

23:20.107 --> 23:26.695
Among the ancient rabbis, there's an idea that spraying up regarding these two instances of water from the rock.

23:28.076 --> 23:31.961
Perhaps they theorized it was the same rock.

23:33.182 --> 23:36.146
They thought maybe that mystical rock had

23:36.258 --> 23:40.484
supernaturally followed Israel through their wilderness journeys.

23:41.926 --> 23:51.159
Now the rabbis who wrote about this came a long time after the days of Paul, but some scholars suspect that they were just documenting an idea that had been talked about much earlier.

23:51.981 --> 23:58.610
We know that Paul had been trained as a young man by the Rabbi Gamaliel, so he was thoroughly schooled in rabbinical thought.

23:59.202 --> 24:09.712
And so it's possible Paul had been exposed to that idea, that he's using that imagery here, that there is this mystical spiritual rock following Israel through the wilderness.

24:11.374 --> 24:24.267
Another way, though, to understand Paul's language about the rock following them is simply to see it as a poetic reference to this water from a rock experience that bookended their wilderness journey.

24:25.007 --> 24:25.808
Start the journey.

24:26.309 --> 24:27.570
There's a rock giving water.

24:28.258 --> 24:30.761
Finish the journey, there's a rock again.

24:32.022 --> 24:37.188
There's really no indication in the biblical text of any rock trailing Israel for 40 years.

24:37.628 --> 24:48.861
In fact, it's hard to imagine the second incident would have even occurred if it had, because why would you be worried about getting water if every time you look behind you there's that rock again following you?

24:49.301 --> 24:51.624
That would just be weird if nothing else.

24:54.027 --> 24:57.010
What had followed them though wasn't the rock.

24:57.858 --> 25:02.324
what had followed them was God, the one who provided for them.

25:03.506 --> 25:08.373
And what Paul saw in those rocks was an image of Christ.

25:09.715 --> 25:14.702
And in that water, an image of the spiritual life that we draw from Christ.

25:16.244 --> 25:23.054
Thirst was an image Jesus often turned to in describing the spiritual condition that people so often find themselves in.

25:23.114 --> 25:26.258
We talked about this some last week in the imagery of hunger,

25:26.594 --> 25:28.857
the manna that they hungered for.

25:28.917 --> 25:34.703
This gnawing sense that there is something essential that is missing.

25:35.624 --> 25:41.551
Some ingredient for a full life that we can't find within ourselves, we can't generate on our own.

25:42.913 --> 25:51.282
Matthew 5, 6, Jesus said, blessed are those who hunger and thirst for righteousness, for they shall be satisfied.

25:52.738 --> 25:56.824
Last week we talked about the story a bit, about the story of the woman at the well, remember?

25:56.905 --> 25:59.809
And how Jesus met with her and they talked about water.

26:00.470 --> 26:05.258
And I wanna just take you back there for a moment, John chapter four verses 13 through 18.

26:06.119 --> 26:15.514
Jesus said to this woman, everyone who drinks in this water, the water at the well that he'd asked her to get him a drink from, everyone who drinks in this water will be thirsty again.

26:15.574 --> 26:20.882
But whoever drinks in the water that I will give him will never be thirsty again.

26:21.442 --> 26:26.409
The water I will give him will we come in him a spring of water, welling up to eternal life.

26:27.691 --> 26:33.920
The woman said to him, well, sir, give me this water so that I'll not be thirsty or have to come here to draw water.

26:35.002 --> 26:37.486
Now you can see she's thinking in terms of physical water.

26:37.586 --> 26:40.029
Jesus is talking about something different, right?

26:40.109 --> 26:41.491
A spiritual water.

26:42.453 --> 26:45.517
Jesus said to her, go call your husband and come here.

26:46.799 --> 26:48.722
The woman answered him, I have no husband.

26:49.602 --> 26:54.768
Jesus said to her, well, you're right in saying I have no husband for you've had five husbands.

26:55.469 --> 26:57.792
