See, I think there's a connection between Jesus' words about unsatisfied thirst and his meddling observation about this woman's fairly checkered marital history.

27:15.794 --> 27:19.538
What does it tell you if a woman has been married five times

27:20.002 --> 27:26.474
and is now back in a relationship once again, just minus the official niceties of a wedding license.

27:28.177 --> 27:34.247
I think it tells us this one believes that the thing she needs above all else is a man in her life.

27:35.991 --> 27:41.981
And despite one failure, one heartbreak after another, she just can't stop going back to that well.

27:43.524 --> 27:44.626
Every new romance

27:45.090 --> 27:52.099
It fills her cup for a while, but it isn't long until things go dry and she finds herself once again looking for love.

27:53.921 --> 28:01.791
In fact, perhaps the fact that she's now living in a common law relationship tells us that even she recognizes that the magic doesn't last.

28:03.273 --> 28:08.920
Why bother with the hassle of planning another wedding and the pain and the expense of another divorce?

28:08.980 --> 28:14.066
Just accept at the outset that this new relationship isn't going to last.

28:15.138 --> 28:19.564
And so love the one you're with and be prepared to rinse and repeat.

28:21.165 --> 28:24.870
It reminds me of some lyrics from a golden oldie.

28:25.851 --> 28:26.792
Maybe you remember this one?

28:26.833 --> 28:33.681
There's some little lyrics.

28:34.202 --> 28:35.884
Darling, I can't go on without you.

28:36.665 --> 28:38.908
This emptiness won't let me live without you.

28:38.928 --> 28:41.851
This loneliness inside, darling, makes me feel half alive.

28:42.252 --> 28:44.114
Baby, I need your loving.

28:44.290 --> 28:46.732
got to have all your loving.

28:49.315 --> 28:52.298
Do you see why to a love-addicted woman like that?

28:52.478 --> 28:58.124
Jesus' words about an unending source of soul satisfaction would be so attractive.

28:59.565 --> 29:03.689
In fact, Jesus didn't simply say the water he would give would satisfy her thirst.

29:03.770 --> 29:09.075
He said it would flow through her to be a source of life to others.

29:10.997 --> 29:12.178
Okay, at this point,

29:12.322 --> 29:15.165
We have several loose strings laying on the table.

29:15.606 --> 29:16.887
Let me just put them out there for you.

29:16.907 --> 29:22.834
Three strings I wanna talk about the first is this part about Moses being in trouble.

29:23.775 --> 29:26.719
Ends up getting in trouble for mistreating a rock, right?

29:26.739 --> 29:29.622
He strikes rock and he's supposed to speak to it and he gets in trouble.

29:29.642 --> 29:32.325
Says you're not gonna be able to go to the promised land because of what you've done.

29:33.367 --> 29:39.634
The second string is that we encounter a lot of angry, thirsty people in a desert

29:39.938 --> 29:43.663
Finding water where they least expect it from a rock.

29:44.303 --> 29:45.305
What was that all about?

29:46.566 --> 29:57.119
And then third, we have a New Testament writer suggesting that the rock that was following them and that is following us, that the rock is Jesus.

29:58.221 --> 29:59.222
And what is that all about?

30:00.564 --> 30:02.586
Well, let me take a stab at pulling them together.

30:03.928 --> 30:09.074
String number one, why did Moses get in so much trouble for striking

30:09.218 --> 30:10.099
the second rock.

30:11.361 --> 30:19.134
As we've been considering all along, the lived history of Israel in the wilderness was more than just a travel log of unusual events.

30:20.236 --> 30:26.265
Jesus and Paul and others saw a greater story being told through those wilderness wanderings.

30:27.608 --> 30:32.095
They saw that God was weaving a tapestry that ultimately formed a picture of Jesus.

30:32.996 --> 30:36.562
And through it, it has lessons to teach us about our walk with Jesus.

30:38.018 --> 30:47.711
In light of that bigger picture, I think it may give some perspective as to why Moses found that striking the second stone got him in so much hot water.

30:49.333 --> 30:59.687
If the stone represents Jesus, then do you see the significance of God telling Moses to strike the first stone with his staff?

31:01.188 --> 31:05.394
Moses' staff had been God's instrument of judgment

31:05.474 --> 31:06.535
against the Egyptians.

31:06.616 --> 31:15.227
In fact, when God tells Moses to take up his staff, he specifically refers back to what Moses had done in judgment toward the Egyptian.

31:15.247 --> 31:16.289
He goes, that's staff.

31:17.571 --> 31:22.677
Every time Moses was commanded to raise that staff, God's judgment had fallen.

31:24.480 --> 31:28.946
